In addition using two-dimensional STE, longitudinal and circumferential LA strain during ventricular systole (LSs) were significantly smaller in patients with paroxysmal AF than in controls (23.8 ± 8.6 versus 32.6 ± 6.5) ([@A10332R18]). In this study, the amount of strain value (%) was assessed as a criterion for LA function and synchrony, however, in our study, we measured the time interval (msec) from the onset of P wave to the onset of pre atrial contraction strain and strain rate curve which seemed to be a far better marker of asynchrony or electromechanical delay in both atria. 5.1. Clinical Implications {#sec16175}
--------------------------

The present study showed that VVI enables the comprehensive assessment of LA synchrony in patients with systolic heart failure with excellent reproducibility. It has been previously shown that in patients with AF, reduced LA strain determined by 2D STE is correlated with fibrosis in LA wall demonstrated by cardiac magnetic resonance imaging, ([@A10332R2]) histologically proven left atrial myocardial fibrosis in patients with mitral valve disease, ([@A10332R19]) CHADS2 risk score ([@A10332R20]) and history of stroke ([@A10332R21]) in patients with persistent AF. Besides these, cardiogenic stroke ([@A10332R21]), prognosis in patients with acute myocardial infarctions ([@A10332R21]) and cardiovascular diseases ([@A10332R22]) and recurrence of AF after pulmonary venous isolation ([@A10332R23]) have been reported to be predictable from LA strain (either determined by tissue Doppler imaging or 2D STE).

